segments.text: On that first semester, did you have some teachers that you realize now were important?
Yeah, I mean, I had an odd collection.
My English teacher was quite good, and I don't remember his name.
My second semester, I had C.K.
Weston, and that was an experience.
Describe the
Well, he was crazy.
I mean, he told all these stories about growing up in a house of ill repute, being raised by prostitutes.
And all of his examples and things were sort of built around this.
And he would get a little loud.
Of course, he was an actor by
his own, I guess, ambition.
And so he acted out in the classroom a lot.
Would tell dirty stories that would curl your hair today.
Fortunately, there were no women at the time.
It didn't make any difference.
And then we, along the way, figured out, of course, that he was the voice of Kyle Field, which helped explain it a bit.
But Esten was a real character.
freshman math teacher, algebra teacher, who was a fifth year senior.
He was a brilliant guy, but very confused.
He would wear his corps uniform with a cowboy belt and buckle.
Or he would wear civilian clothes with his corps belt and shoes.
And he was still going through the ROTC program because he had to finish, I guess he probably started there.
But he was an odd duck.
A fellow named Doug With was a teacher that took Animal Science 107 that freshman year, who's now dead, was a very high quality teacher.
Probably had been an ag teacher or a 4-H leader or something, and has been very involved in livestock youth programs.
And he was a good teacher.
Chemistry was a guy named, gee, I can't remember his name.
What I remember about him was we had Chemistry 101 at old chemistry lecture hall, probably seat 300 kids.
And if you happen to doze off, he would throw a piece of chalk at you.
And a friend of mine named Andy Combs could never stay awake, and he sat in the next.
And you drew chairs.
They assigned you by numbers to the chairs.
So I had to stay alert, because I knew there was going to be a piece of chalk coming at me.
Targeted for Andy, but he wasn't that accurate.
But I mean, I can't imagine today either, a professor standing at the front of the room.
Of course, they probably don't have chalk anymore.
They're teaching with PowerPoint.
As you got into the academic program, what did you realize were the unwritten rules about going to class and so forth?
Well, in those days, if you were a distinguished student, you were exempt from class.
Now, that sounds like a strange concept.
But it was very coveted because you did have other things that frequently got in the way.
So back to my earlier point, one of the good things about being a distinguished student the first semester is that I had some choices the second semester.
What you figured out, though, is even if you were comatose, you better be in that class.
They were keeping score.
Oh, I remember the fellow's name in chemistry.
I think his name was Doc Little.
We had chemistry lab at 1 o'clock on Friday afternoon.
That was one of the bad parts about someone else doing my schedule.
But when we had a pop quiz, he would come in the window.
He would be on the ledge.
of the chemistry building, come in the window and throw chicken feathers in the room.
And Love just had a great time with this.

And by the way, that was canceled in November because as I walked from Duncan Dining Hall back to my dorm room to get my chemistry lab stuff, a fellow came to the end of dorm seven yelling, the president has been shot.
And I looked back, and I was a freshman, and I looked at the guy, and I said, don't joke about something like that.
And he said, no joke.
Went back, turned that little phonograph Victrola thing on, had a radio in it, sure enough, and learned that he had been shot.
What other, let's center on that.
What did you and your buddies think about that event, and what did you all do that night, and so forth?
You know, it's interesting.
Thinking back on it, I had very much the same sensation that I had with the bonfire event this year, in that there was this huge tragedy.
You were helpless and uncertain about what was going on.
And frankly, in those days, it was worse than that, because you didn't know if it might be some kind of conspiracy or attack against the country.
It was really very much unknown.
So we sat around in our rooms with each other in sort of groups and talked about what was going on.
And then it happened, I guess, on must have been
Monday or Tuesday, I don't remember, bonfire was canceled.
It was partially built, but not completely.

And I remember going to meeting a high school friend of mine who was going to UT and went to Austin and spent the night with him and his, I think, sister just to get away and sort of regroup and try to figure out what was going on.
And then the game was played.
It was a great ball game.
In fact, Texas was the national champion that year.
We beat them in Kyle Field, but the refs gave them seven points.
And we failed to pull it off.
But why I know we beat them was I was sitting where the, if you remember where the old horseshoe in Kyle Field was,
there was a entrance for the band to march through.

I was the first guy on the first row next to that with a date, Fish Harned's sister from Fort Worth, when I saw Jim Willenborg catch the intercept pass in the end zone and slide out of the end zone on his knees, and they called him out of bounds.
So I had a front row seat to record this.
Back to getting broken into the core, describe the routine for a fish in the dining hall.
This is in Duncan.
You're in the new area.
Well, you know, interestingly, the dorms were
Compared to where I was living at home, they were quite nice.
I mean, they were brick.
They had concrete floors, which were waxed.
We had concrete floors.
Still steam heated with no air conditioning.
But they were Spartan, but they were OK.
The dining hall was a horrible disaster.
One of the problems in those days was you could never get enough to eat.
I mean, this was a...
This was a period when we went through with what I consider probably A&M was having trouble getting anyone to come here.
So among the group, you got a lot of sadists signed up.
And for whatever reason, the dining hall became a place where the harassment level was high, and intimidation was high, and it wasn't a lot of fun.
Now, the other thing is we had yell practice two nights a week.

uh it was tradition quote that c1 and d1 be on the front row of kyle field on the 50-yard line with their guidons next to each other which meant you marched in you stood at attention you had the prayer you sat down you drank one glass of milk
You had the announcements and you left.
So two nights a week, you got nothing to eat other than you might be able to slosh down a little milk.
By the way, another part of the yell practice routine was that
They moved the yell practice from the Grove to Kyle Field, maybe the previous fall or maybe that fall.
And we're standing on the front row, me and my fish buddy have the guide on.
And this guy comes walking down the track, waving and shouting and saying hello to everybody, throwing bags of popcorn up into the, and you know, you're supposed to be standing at attention.
And the fellow was sort of chubby, balding, round-faced.
And my official lady leans over to me and says, who is that?
And I said, I think it's President Rutter.
Well, it was Lupo.
And Lupo was out, of course, drumming up business among the good ol' eggs.
And I'll never forget that mistake that I made.
President Rutter, fortunately, never knew it.
But back to the dining hall, if you weren't doing Hot Corner, which was through the family-style system where the meals came to,

Or you were a, this is a word that can't be used in contemporary terms, but it started with an N, and it was the person that served the junior or senior at that table, that you were his N. And those two were sort of specific assignments.
And then the rest of the time you were just getting harassed.
Now the good advantage was if you could find a time when you didn't have a class after chow, you could hang around until everybody else departed in a meal hound.
You had to endure a lot to get there, but you did.
It was one of the ways you got food.
There were a lot of little playful things that went on.
You often got an assignment to crawl through a few tables and light someone's bib.
You've probably heard of this little deal.
Or we had a few other games, like we played a game called Cal.

And you'd have two freshmen across from each other, each who would try to take an entire bottle of, at that time, cream-reproduced milk, put it in their mouths, and then stare at each other while the upperclassmen told them jokes.
And then whoever, of course, broke first, spit the milk on the other guy.
And it was really not, it was great fun, if you think about it.
And then there were routines about you had to know all this campusology so people would ask you questions.
And you got to eat if you answered them and you didn't if you didn't.
Were those called Cush questions?
Well, Cush questions were for dessert.
Oh, but there were just of these?
There was campusology questions throughout.
And of course you had to call all the food by its proper name, which I had trouble remembering.
I wasn't a very good freshman.
What I figured out early on, which I think was sort of the standard way of surviving, was two things.
One is it was a game, and you had to understand it was a game if you got real serious about it.
you were in trouble.
And the second was you had the only friends you had were your fish buddies.
You'd occasionally find an upperclassman who would befriend you, drop handles and was sort of a place to escape to.
But it was rare.
The fish buddies, it was a Darwinian existence that you survived through your freshman friends.
And you found ways to answer back through those freshman friends.
So everybody knew that the game was being played that way.
Do you remember any retaliation that you and your fish buddies wreaked on some people?
Yeah, there were a few popular methods, all handed down in terms of the methodology.
The favorite thing was drowning out.
I never did understand why the rule was such, but you couldn't lock your doors at night, even if you were an upperclassman.

And so, but the old doors in the, in those dorms, if you, what you would do is you would vee the, you would open the main door and the other closet door and they veed together the doorknobs hooked and it provided a airway path through the room.
And I guess the reason they didn't lock them was because they couldn't stand the heat.
But what you do is you'd fill a, they had old plastic trash cans, probably 50-gallon trash cans.
And you would fill that pretty much with water.
And then you would go into an upperclassman's room and two guys or three guys, and you would wash them right out of the bed with that 50-gallon can of water.
We had one, we had a sophomore frog
came in at mid-semester his sophomore year, and our assignment given to us by the sophomore class was to drown him out every night his spring semester.
So we dutifully had to get somebody assigned to, and it was sort of like after a while it got to be a joke because he knew it was coming.
literally every night.
Now, they finally called it off after a while, but this got to be pretty tortuous for everybody.
In hindsight, was he a bad egg?
Did he deserve this kind?
Well, he was a frog sophomore, so he hadn't gone through the same experience they'd gone through, and so they considered this sort of a duty.
As it turned out, he was sort of a different kind of fellow, but not that different.
And the assignment came from his classmates?
His classmates.
The sophomores?
Right.
We got another assignment which in a way was sort of tragic.
We had two juniors who were in a bit of a pitched battle.
And one of them was the first sergeant.
And we got the assignment of taking the first sergeant, putting him in a mattress cover.
Our mattresses had cotton covers that tied back in those days for sanitation purposes, I assume.
Took him out of his bed, put him in the mattress cover, took him out to the site now where Kruger Dunn Aston Mosier is, was then a drill area.
Took a logging chain, attached it to the sack, and tied him up into an oak tree.
And then we all go back to our dorm and try to go back to sleep, of course, with your heart going 90 miles an hour.
What I remember is the sound of the chain clanking as it came up the stairs.
And then the next thing I knew, you had all the freshmen up in the hallway.
And we were doing something called manual of arms with our foot lockers.
Now, you know what manual of arms is.
Boy, when you're doing right shoulder, left shoulder, present arms, try imagining doing that with a full foot lock.
And this is probably, by this time, it's 1 or 2 in the morning, and our CO, Charlie Fisher, comes out and finds all this going on and shuts it down.
And as a result, both Parker, the first sergeant, and this other junior were kicked out of the Corps.
And one of them might have even been kicked out of school.
I can't remember.
This was not an unusual event.
I mean, this is a pretty standard event.
It's just that it got elevated to the point where there was a feud, and we were in the middle of it.
So that the footlocker was... A little like a rifle.
That was too severe, the footlocker routine.
Oh, yeah.
But the drowning out... No, no, that's okay.
That was okay.
Yeah.
And there were Babbo bombs, which I'm sure you've heard of, which...
Bevel bombs were fine as long as you took the metal ends out.
See, bevel cans had aluminum or metal.
And what you learned was you take that out and you put ankle tape, basically, on the ends of the can.
The best ones were the ones that were hooked up to a cherry bomb, hooked up to the light switch so that you had it hooked to the room.
And then when they flipped the switch, it blew up and went all over the room.

but one of the best things that we did though in retaliation paid dearly for it but uh our our co as i said was sort of a gentle fellow and he decided that he didn't really want to work on the bonfire and this was in those days you built a bonfire in roughly 10 days as soon as the rice game ended
which was always the week before UT.
If it was here, after the game, you immediately went to the cut site.
If it was in Houston, you drove back and went to work at the cut site the next day.
Well, anyway, Fisher decided that he was a senior and he was tired of bonfire and he was going to go home to Cuero for the weekend.
At the time, they were building what's now the president's home.
And there was plenty of brick and sand and mortar available.
And we had some rather ingenious freshmen in the outfit.
And we managed to lug over there enough brick, sand, and mortar to mortar up Charlie Fisher's door from the inside.
And it was on the fourth floor.

Byron Watts who was the ringleader of this had a grappling hook and a rope so that he could get down to the co-conspirators upperclassmen on the third floor corner room and get out after he had finished the brick job so when Charlie comes back on Sunday evening from Cuero to get in his room he puts his key in the old metal door and lock and pushes and nothing happens
And no matter what he does, and of course the hinges are on the inside, this thing is, it's literally like a castle moat.
There's no way to get in it.
The physical plant people had to finally come over, and I think they just had to break the door down.
I don't even remember how they got in.
I just know that we had a great time with that little event.
And no one got kicked out for that?
Oh, no.
No, that was just good bull.
And did anyone admit...
to any authority as to who?
Only years later.
Let's see.
Describe the bonfire routine.
You said you all came back from the rice game and started.
How far away was the cut area?
Do you remember?
Don't really remember.
I would say probably
It was probably five, 10 miles, something like that.
We would leave the dorm, go to Duncan Field, get on flatbed trucks in the middle of what seemed like the middle of the night.
And those trucks would haul us out to the cut site.
And then we, our outfit responsibility was at the cut site, and then we were the final guards
of the bonfire, right before it was lighted.
That's all changed through time.
Did you and your buddies, did you all cut logs?
No, only upperclassmen could either use a chainsaw or an ax.
Freshmen were just grunts.
We cut logs.
what were known as F-sticks.
And these were oak saplings, probably three or four inches in diameter, and then long enough to get a log in the middle and three freshman on each side.
And you lined the sticks up, rolled the log on it, and then through just sheer, I mean, I can imagine how the pyramids were built.
That's how you built.
the bonfire.

And then you would haul it to the truck, the three kids on the truck side would stick the sticks on the bed, duck under, come out, and then the three on the other side would roll it on and there you went until you got the trucks loaded.
And as far as you were aware, this routine was copied from the previous years.
And as far as you know, what injuries were there, if any, that year?
Nicks and cuts and exhaustion and classes missed and that's it.

i you know i think i've reflected on this a lot and it's not the purpose of the uh of the discussion but there were a couple of things one was it was the the core chain of command uh was although there was a lot of horseplay and craziness at the end of the day the one thing that was emphasized was safety and procedure and you know you you did you did things and if you screwed up
you were still in that chain of command.
I mean, it could be dealt with.
It was not a sort of a separate student organization without that kind of core discipline and attention.
The other thing was that we tended to specialize.
Certain corps outfits were responsible for certain things.
What I remember is the band
was at the site offloading.
And then there were engineering outfits responsible for actually doing the stack.
There was very little, almost nobody on the stack.
I mean, it was rare for anybody to be up top.
What they typically did was go up there

do some topping out and cleaning up but but most of the stack work was done by tilting the logs up from the bottom and building out in a teepee form so you didn't have the kids exposed like they were and this was on the drill field or Duncan field Duncan field and it already moved over there right and as far as you recall about how many stacks high there's only one stack
I mean, how many stacks?
I don't know.
It all looked like a big Indian teepee.
And the tops of each log were not cut off exactly like a... No.
It was very roughly formed, which probably, you know, helped its stability because everything tended to be intertwined and interlocking.
And it was, you know, a lot has been made about the 1969 bonfire being the tallest ever.
If you look at it, it's tall only because there's a long center pole and a few sticks at the top, but it was really pretty symptomatic of the bonfires of the time.
It was mostly a lean-to kind of teepee formation.

so y'all worked about uh let's see you worked on it but that bonfire was not burned was not burned we worked on it for i guess a week through the weekend prior to well that's not right kennedy was killed on friday

so it was it was friday that we stopped work and it was that saturday and sunday that i went to austin and then of course they announced that the and do you remember i don't what happened to those logs the public was invited to come and take whatever they wanted that's right there was no and then i guess somebody physical plant probably cleaned it up when it was all over but
Another interesting thing, I went back to the game.
You remember the old tradition that if we beat University of Texas on Thanksgiving, we got Monday off.
Well, we didn't beat them, but Rudder gave us Monday off and we all thought he was a hero.
because of the way that we were treated by the referees.
Your mention of President Rutter, when do you first recall seeing him or having any interaction with him as a student?
You know, I mean, I knew he was the president as a freshman, and I probably, you know, there were some, I remember a Guyon Hall event early in our time.
It was the old Guyon Hall, when you look left and look right, you know, and half of you are going to be gone speech.
And I think Rudder was probably at that speech, but he was sort of a distant icon, and I didn't really know anything about him.
He was, Rutter was a guy that frankly didn't have a lot of personality.
I mean he was a strong-willed, firm, resolute sort of fellow who, I mean he had some good humor about him, don't misunderstand me, but I couldn't see it as a young student.
Probably my first real exposure came to him through the student senate.
We had a student senate, I was on the student senate, and he would meet with us occasionally, especially on controversial issues, and we had a few in our day.
We had a faculty member in veterinary medicine that was fired, I guess, would be the proper way.
A tenured faculty member, in fact.
And Rutter was the guy who made the decision.
And of course, the faculty were all over him to the degree that they could in those days.
And the student newspaper was all over him.
And a friend of mine, this was actually, I guess, our senior, fall of our senior year.
A friend of mine named Tommy DeFrank was the editor of the battalion and Tommy took Rutter on and Rutter told him, you know, one more article, Tommy, and you're gone.
Tommy, citing First Amendment rights, took one more shot at it and sure enough he was gone.
And so we had a little controversy surrounding all that, but probably my sophomore or junior year through the Student Senate would have been the first real.
Now in those days the Student Senate met in a small second floor room in the MSC.
There were probably
I don't know, 20, 25 people, whereas today it's hundreds, you know, and that's sort of become the English Parliament.
But in those days it was small because the place was small.
That freshman year, did you go on court trips?
Yes.
Describe that.
I probably shouldn't.
The first one I remember going to was to the Rice Corps trip in Houston.
And a couple of buddies of mine, one in my outfit and one that was a high school friend from Trent, Texas, the Trent Gorillas, was the other person.
And I guess there were four of us, because we couldn't afford to get one.
And we got a room in the old Rice Hotel downtown.
And we got someone to buy some booze for us.

And after the game, which I'm sure we lost, I can't remember, but pretty sure we did, we went back to the room and boozed it up and had a good time and made the downtown streets of Houston along with a lot of other ne'er-do-wells.
The thing I remember most was there were tiebacks on the curtains in the old rooms.
that were made much resembling a crapper cord, you know, that you wore in the corps.
So we absconded with those curtain pullbacks and decided they would be our crapper cords as freshmen in the corps.
And years later, I came across that thing in some stuff my mother had kept.
She probably thought it was for real.
You didn't have a date on that?
Did not have a date.
What about the Dallas or Fort Worth?
We had a great time in Dallas because I had a friend named Sarah Lee Moyer who I went to high school with who had gone to North Texas.
And our court trip that year was to Fort Worth.
And I had called Sara Lee to see if she might know of some girls at North Texas that would be interested in a date.
Well, she said, I think so.
And so we all head up there.
And she's arranged, I don't know, probably eight or 10 kids to have dates.
They were gorgeous little girls.
Everybody had a great time.
We just had a ball.
And everything was fine.
until our sophomore year when we went to the Corps trip in Dallas, at which time I had people lining up at my door saying, hey, you think we could do this again?
Well, I did.
And Sarah Lee complied.
But what she failed to tell me was this was the same weekend as North Texas homecoming.
So the quality of the dates
went downhill just a little from the first year to the next.
So I wasn't nearly as popular the second time around as I was the first.
